# Background

Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) occurs when a victim's browser is tricked into sending an authenticated request to a vulnerable application without the user's consent.

Some applications attempt to prevent CSRF attacks by checking the `Referer` header. While this can provide an additional security layer, it is unreliable if implemented incorrectly.

In this lab, the application only verifies whether the trusted domain appears anywhere inside the `Referer` header instead of validating the actual origin. This weak validation can be bypassed by embedding the trusted domain within an attacker-controlled URL.

---

# Reconnaissance

After logging in, changing the email address generated the following request:

```http
POST /my-account/change-email HTTP/2

email=test@example.com
```

Observations:

* No CSRF token was present.
* Authentication relied exclusively on the session cookie.
* The request was accepted only when the `Referer` header passed validation.

---

# Vulnerability Analysis

Testing the endpoint with Burp Suite Repeater showed that requests with an unrelated `Referer` header were rejected.

Example:

```http
Referer: https://evil.com/
```

However, when the trusted lab domain appeared anywhere inside the URL, the request was accepted:

```http
Referer: https://evil.com/?0a123456.web-security-academy.net
```

This confirmed that the application performed a simple substring comparison instead of validating the request origin.

Because the browser automatically includes the `Referer` header when submitting forms, an attacker can abuse this behavior to bypass the protection.

---

# Attack Flow

```text
Attacker
    │
    ▼
Hosts malicious HTML page
    │
    ▼
Victim visits attacker-controlled page
    │
    ▼
Browser automatically submits authenticated form
    │
    ▼
Referer contains trusted domain as substring
    │
    ▼
Application accepts request
    │
    ▼
Victim's email address is changed
```

